{"title_page": "Penn State Nittany Lions women's ice hockey", "text_new": "{{Infobox college ice hockey team\n|team_name = Penn State Nittany Lions women's ice hockey\n|image = Penn State Nittany Lions hockey logo.svg\n|image_size =\n|university = Pennsylvania State University\n|current=2016\u201317 Penn State Nittany Lions women's ice hockey season\n|conference = College Hockey America\n|conference_short = CHA\n|coach = [[Jeff Kampersal]]\n|coach_year = 3rd\n|arena = [[Pegula Ice Arena]]\n|capacity = 5,782<ref name=\"capacity\">{{Cite web|work=Penn State University|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/pegula-ice-arena|title=The Home of Penn State Hockey|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref>\n|location = University Park, Pennsylvania\n|NCAAchampion =  \n|NCAAfrozenfour = \n|NCAAtourneys = \n|ACHAchampion = \n|ACHAtourneys = \n|conference_tournament = \n|conference_season = \n}}\n\n'''Penn State Nittany Lions women's ice hockey'''<ref name=\"bond\">{{Cite web|last=Gentile|first=Eddie|work=[[The Daily Collegian (Penn State)|The Daily Collegian]]|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2008/11/20/lady_icers_bond_through_advers.aspx|title=Lady Icers bond through adversity|date=November 20, 2008|accessdate=September 13, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306042300/http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2008/11/20/lady_icers_bond_through_advers.aspx|archivedate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> is a [[college ice hockey]] program that has represented [[Penn State University]] in [[Division I (NCAA)|National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division I]] and [[College Hockey America]] (CHA) since the 2012\u201313 season.<ref name=\"press\">{{Cite web|last=Staff|work=[[Penn State University]]|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-hockey/spec-rel/091710aab.html|title=Penn State to Add Men's and Women's Varsity Ice Hockey|date=September 17, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> The program was preceded by a club team that competed at the [[American Collegiate Hockey Association|American Collegiate Hockey Association (ACHA) Division 1]] level, primarily as a member of [[Eastern Collegiate Women's Hockey League]] (ECWHL).<ref name=\"miss\">{{Cite web|last=Riley|first=Duncan|work=The Inquisitr|url=http://www.inquisitr.com/16368/miss-america-finalist-tara-wheeler-also-an-ice-hockey-goalie/|title=Miss America Finalist Tara Wheeler also an Ice Hockey Goalie|date=January 24, 2009|accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"records10\">{{Cite web|work=[[American Collegiate Hockey Association|ACHA]] |url=http://achahockey.org/team_stats.php?team_id=13191&league_id=1064|title=Penn State University Records|year=2010|accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"ecwhl\">{{cite web |work=[[Eastern Collegiate Women's Hockey League|ECWHL]]|url=http://php.scripts.psu.edu/clubs/up/ladyicers/ecwhl/teams.php|title=ECWHL Teams|date=2006\u20132007 |accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> Penn State plays its home games at [[Pegula Ice Arena]] in [[University Park, Pennsylvania]].\n\n==History==\n\n===ACHA years===\n\nPenn State's first women's hockey team \u2013 a club team called the \"Lady Icers\" \u2013 began play in the 1996\u201397 season, after students Ellen Bradley and Kathy Beckford recruited players from around campus and Vinnie Scalamogna, the assistant manager of the [[Penn State Ice Pavilion]] (then the university's sole ice facility), as coach.<ref name=\"origin\">{{cite news |last=Lello |first=Michael |publisher=The Daily Collegian|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_209c9ca8-72f8-5af8-b4cc-ff6a20a74bc6.html|title=Women's hockey team takes the ice|date=November 12, 1996 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The Lady Icers' first game, a 5\u20134 win over the Susquehanna Rockettes (an adult club team), took place on February 1, 1997.<ref name=\"rockettes\">{{cite news |last=Lello|first=Michael|publisher=The Daily Collegian|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archives/article_74a84589-91b3-5a1d-92ab-f1f07f8e3e5d.html|title=Lady Icers pick up win in inaugural game |date=February 3, 1997|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The team was intermittently successful over its 16 years of existence, winning six conference regular season or playoff titles and qualifying for the ACHA National Tournament six times, peaking with a third-place finish at the end of the 2001-02 season.<ref name=\"facts\">{{Cite web|work=[[Penn State University]] |url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-hockey/spec-rel/091710aah.html|title=Fact Sheet|date=September 17, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\nPenn State concluded its time in the ACHA in February 2012, with eventual NCAA leader Josh Brandwene as head coach. That season, the Lady Icers played a mixed schedule, featuring ACHA and ECWHL opponents as well as eleven games against [[Division I (NCAA)|NCAA Division I]] and [[Division III (NCAA)|Division III]] teams. PSU finished the year by claiming the ECWHL regular season title, but then losing to [[Rhode Island Rams women's ice hockey|Rhode Island]] in the league's playoff championship game.<ref name=\"motivated1112\">{{cite news|last=Rodas|first=Mark|publisher=[[The Daily Collegian (Penn State)|The Daily Collegian]]|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2012/02/22/lady_icers.aspx|title=Lady Icers staying motivated|date=February 22, 2012|accessdate=March 23, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121211122026/http://www.collegian.psu.edu/archive/2012/02/22/lady_icers.aspx|archivedate=December 11, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Move to NCAA===\n\nAfter years of speculation<ref name=\"close\">{{Cite web|last=Giger|first=Cory|work=[[Altoona Mirror]]|url=http://www.altoonamirror.com/page/content.detail/id/541062/Penn-State--close--to-adding-arena--Division-I-hockey.html?nav=746|title=Penn State 'close' to adding arena, Division I hockey|date=August 6, 2010|accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"dominos\">{{cite web |last=Starman|first=Dave|work=U.S. College Hockey Online|url=http://www.uscho.com/news/id,18751/CommentaryWhichWayWillDominosFallAfterPennStatesIntroduction.html|title=Which Way Will Dominos Fall After Penn State\u2019s Introduction?|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=September 13, 2010}}</ref> the program transitioned to the [[NCAA Division I]] level along with the PSU [[Penn State Nittany Lions men's ice hockey|men's ice hockey team]] for the 2012\u201313 season. The move was made possible thanks to a Penn State-record $88 million (later increased to $102 million) donation, announced on September 17, 2010, from [[Terrence Pegula]], a Penn State alumnus and billionaire hockey fan, and his wife Kim.<ref name=\"historic\">{{Cite web|last=Staff|work=[[Penn State University]]|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/m-hockey/spec-rel/091710aaa.html|title=Pegulas Commit Historic Gift To Penn State For New Arena And Hockey Program |date=September 17, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> The donation primarily paid for the completion of a new [[Pegula Ice Arena|5,782-seat, $89 million ice arena]] to replace the undersized and aging 1,350-seat [[Penn State Ice Pavilion]], which was deemed inadequate for long-term NCAA play.<ref name=\"close\"/><ref name=\"add\">{{Cite web |last=Ciskie|first=Bruce|work=[[FanHouse]] |url=http://nhl.fanhouse.com/2010/09/13/penn-state-reportedly-set-to-add-hockey/|title=Penn State Reportedly Set to Add Hockey|date=September 13, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"announcement\">{{Cite web|last=Wodon|first=Adam|work=College Hockey News|url=http://www.collegehockeynews.com/news/2010/09/16_pennstate.php|title=Penn State Announcement Expected Friday|date=September 16, 2010|accessdate=September 17, 2010}}</ref> [[Pegula Ice Arena]] opened in September 2013, after the Nittany Lions played their first NCAA season in the [[Penn State Ice Pavilion|Ice Pavilion]].\n\nIn May 2011 the university hired Brandwene as the first varsity women's hockey head coach.<ref>{{cite news|last=AP Staff|work=[[Daily Journal (Indiana)|Daily Journal]]|url=http://www.dailyjournal.net/view/story/56afcb1e34ae4793a297760fa75b1073/HKW--Penn-St-Coach/|title=Penn St turns to veteran coach, administrator, alum Josh Brandwene to lead D-I women's hockey|date=May 31, 2011|accessdate=June 23, 2011}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On June 21, 2011, former Lady Icers head coach Mo Stroemel and Gina Kearns joined Brandwene's staff as assistants. Kearns had been an assistant with the [[Neumann Knights|Neumann University Knights]], coaching there from 2009 until 2011.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Penn State University]] |url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-hockey/spec-rel/062111aaa.html|title=Penn State Women's Hockey Adds Stroemel and Kearns to Coaching Staff|date=June 21, 2011|accessdate=June 26, 2011}}</ref> In September 2011, Penn State was accepted into [[College Hockey America]] for the 2012\u201313 season, becoming the fifth member of the conference after [[Wayne State University|Wayne State]] abruptly ended their women's hockey program, dropping league membership to only four teams for the 2011\u201312 season.<ref name=\"Wayne_State_women_drop\">{{cite web|last=Staff|work=U.S. College Hockey Online |url=http://www.uscho.com/2011/05/27/wayne-state-drops-womens-program-cha-left-with-four-teams/|title=Wayne State drops women\u2019s program; CHA left with four team s|date=May 27, 2011 |accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===NCAA===\n\n[[File:Hannah Hoenshell.jpg|thumb|Hannah Hoenshell, Penn State's leading scorer in 2013\u201314]]\n\nThe Nittany Lions launched their NCAA era in stunning fashion, with a 5\u20133 victory over [[Vermont Catamounts women's ice hockey|Vermont]] at [[Gutterson Fieldhouse]] on October 6, 2012, helped by a pair of goals each from Micayla Catanzariti and Shannon Yoxheimer.<ref name=\"UVMwin1\">{{cite web|work=Penn State University|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-hockey/recaps/100612aaa.html|title=Nittany Lions Take Inaugural Opener at Vermont, 5\u20133 |date=October 6, 2012|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Behind a roster led by forward and captain Taylor Gross, forward Jenna Welch and goaltender Nicole Paniccia (each a transfer from the [[Connecticut Huskies women's ice hockey|University of Connecticut]]), and featuring eight Lady Icers holdovers (including Gross) along with 17 freshmen, PSU climbed to 5\u20138\u20131 overall on November 17, 2012 with its first-ever [[College Hockey America|CHA]] win, 3\u20132 over fellow former ACHA program [[Lindenwood Lady Lions ice hockey|Lindenwood]].<ref name=\"firstCHAwin\">{{cite web|work=Penn State University|url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-hockey/recaps/111712aaa.html |title=Women's Hockey Earns First CHA Win, 3\u20132, over Lindenwood|date=November 17, 2012|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The Nittany Lions skidded the rest of the way through, managing only two wins (both against [[Division III (NCAA)|NCAA Division III]] [[Chatham University]]) over the final 21 games of the season, including a sweep by [[RIT Tigers women's ice hockey|RIT]] in the first round of the [[College Hockey America|CHA]] playoffs.<ref name=\"1213schedule\">{{cite web|work=College Hockey Stats|url=http://collegehockeystats.net/1213/schedules/psuw|title=Penn State Nittany Lions (Women) 2012\u20132013 Schedule and Results|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013\u201314 season again began encouragingly, with another win at [[Vermont Catamounts women's ice hockey|Vermont]] and a split in the team's first [[Pegula Ice Arena]] games, on October 18 and 19, 2013 against [[Union Dutchwomen ice hockey|Union]].<ref name=\"1314schedule\">{{cite web|work=College Hockey Stats|url=http://collegehockeystats.net/1314/schedules/psuw|title=Penn State Nittany Lions (Women) 2013\u20132014 Schedule and Results|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> However, despite eight ties or overtime losses and thanks largely to scoring just 1.36 times per game,<ref name=\"1314stats\">{{cite web|work=College Hockey Stats|url=http://collegehockeystats.net/1314/teamstats/psuw|title=Penn State Nittany Lions (Women) 2013\u20132014 Team Statistics |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> the Nittany Lions regressed to four wins overall and were once again swept by [[RIT Tigers women's ice hockey|RIT]] in the first round of the [[College Hockey America|CHA]] playoffs.<ref name=\"1314schedule\"/>\n\nPSU found its greatest success in the NCAA era during the 2014-15 season, when the team posted its first winning record (17-16-4), highest CHA standings position (tied for third) and first CHA playoff series win (against Lindenwood) before falling to Syracuse in the CHA semifinals,<ref name=\"1415schedule\">{{cite web|work=College Hockey Stats |url=http://collegehockeystats.net/1415/schedules/psuw|title=Penn State Nittany Lions (Women) 2014\u20132015 Schedule and Results|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> thanks largely to the [[Minnetonka, MN]]-native duo of Laura Bowman and Amy Petersen, who combined for 27 goals. One obvious season highlight was a December 2014 sweep of then-No. 6 Mercyhurst, the Nittany Lions' first and second wins against a ranked team and against the perennially-powerful Lakers.<ref name=\"hurst1\">{{cite web|work=Penn State Athletics |url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-hockey/recaps/121214aaa.html|title=Penn State Upsets No. 6 Mercyhurst, 2-1|date=December 12, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"hurst2\">{{cite web|work=Penn State Athletics |url=http://www.gopsusports.com/sports/w-hockey/recaps/121314aaa.html|title=Nittany Lions Sweep No. 6 Mercyhurst|date=December 13, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> However, the team slid slightly backwards in 2015-16, matching the previous season's CHA standings placement and playoff results (a first-round sweep of RIT followed by a triple-overtime loss to Syracuse in the semifinals) but finishing only 12-19-6 overall.<ref name=\"1516schedule\">{{cite web|work=College Hockey Stats|url=http://collegehockeystats.net/1516/schedules/psuw|title=Penn State Nittany Lions (Women) 2015\u20132016 Schedule and Results|accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2014 offseason controversy====\n\nA few weeks after the conclusion of the 2013\u201314 season, a group of thirteen players spoke with Penn State Associate Athletic Director Charmelle Green to \"express their frustration with Brandwene and concerns about the future of the program.\"<ref name=\"controversy\">{{cite web|last=Nelson|first=Kristen|work=The Daily Collegian |url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/sports/women_hockey/article_686d4aaa-c995-11e3-9954-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Seven women's hockey players cut from team|date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Seven of this group were subsequently cut from the team, including Jessica Desorcie, Darby Kern, Cara Mendelson, Brooke Meyer, Katie Murphy, Birdie Shaw and Madison Smiddy.<ref name=\"controversy\" /> Murphy was the most outspoken of the cuts, telling Penn State student newspaper ''[[The Daily Collegian]]'' that \"[Brandwene] talked to us like we were children. Three or four weeks he would go without even looking at me or without even talking to me. He\u2019s a bully. That\u2019s the best word I can think of for him,\" and that \"The girls don\u2019t respect the coach because he hasn\u2019t earned our respect at all. He\u2019s been my coach for three years and I tried my hardest to respect him and I still don\u2019t have the respect for him that I should have for a head coach because he\u2019s not a good coach.\"<ref name=\"controversy\" />\n\nOver the days following Murphy's comments, others formerly involved with the program, including strength and conditioning coach Rob McLean<ref name=\"mclean\">{{cite web |last=Nelson |first=Kristen|work=The Daily Collegian|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/sports/women_hockey/article_05bed14e-cb75-11e3-8c75-001a4bcf6878.html|title=Former women\u2019s hockey strength and conditioning coach voices opinion on Brandwene, player cuts|date=April 24, 2014|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> as well as outgoing transfer players Katie Zinn and Taylor McGee<ref name=\"zinn\">{{cite web|last=Nelson|first=Kristen|work=The Daily Collegian|url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/sports/women_hockey/article_0e2de2ee-ca93-11e3-80da-001a4bcf6878.html |title=Transfers react to recent women\u2019s hockey cuts|date=April 23, 2014|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> also spoke critically of Brandwene.\n\n====2016 offseason controversy====\n\nThe program again found itself the subject of negative headlines in March 2016, as Murphy, Mendelson, Shaw and others told or retold their stories to ''The Daily Collegian''.<ref name=\"controversy2\">{{cite web|last=Mallon|first=Morganne|work=The Daily Collegian |url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/features/article_6440c3fe-ef35-11e5-a8c6-2b9904aa8e15.html|title=Former Penn State women's hockey players allege emotional abuse by current head coach Josh Brandwene|date=March 21, 2016 |accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> One of the chief allegations made concerned the handling of the 2014 complaint, with Murphy and Shaw claiming that Green promised the group filing the complaint confidentiality before subsequently burying the issue and turning their names over to Brandwene, who cut them - actions that would appear to be in violation of Penn State athletics guidelines. Several stories of emotional abuse were included as well. One anonymous former player said that Brandwene told her to lose weight in order to play more, while Shaw recounted an incident in which Brandwene physically knocked her stick from her hands while saying \"don't worry, you won't be needing that today.\"<ref name=\"controversy2\" /> Shaw also said that Brandwene ruined the sport for her, to the point where she wouldn't allow her kids to play.\n\nAs with the 2014 situation, others came forward in the following days, including 2011-12 ACHA team players Katie Vaughan, Ashton Schaffer and Abbey Dufoe.<ref name=\"controversy3\">{{cite web |last=Mallon|first=Morganne|work=The Daily Collegian |url=http://www.collegian.psu.edu/features/article_00a76194-f22e-11e5-aaef-a7e738940165.html|title=More former Penn State women's hockey players voice allegations|date=March 25, 2016 |accessdate=March 25, 2016}}</ref> Vaughan said that \"it became clear to me that this man has a destructive personality and he meant the team no well-being\"<ref name=\"controversy3\" /> while recalling a conversation involving Brandwene pressing her about personal issues. Both she and Schaffer detailed other instances of [[emotional manipulation]] that almost caused them to end decade-plus playing careers, while Dufoe flatly said that \"no one should be treated like that.\"<ref name=\"controversy3\" /> One father of an anonymous current player said that his daughter would transfer if Brandwene is retained as coach, and that \"he has heard other parents say the same thing.\"<ref name=\"controversy3\" />\n\n====2017 offseason coaching change====\n\nOn April 19, 2017, Josh Brandwene retired from coaching, and on June 1, 2017, Penn State announced the hiring of longtime Princeton women's hockey head coach Jeff Kampersal to lead the Penn State women's hockey team beginning with the 2017\u201318 season.\n\n==Season by season results==\n\nSeason-by-season results as of the conclusion of 2015\u201316 season.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Year-by-Year Results|publisher=Penn State Women's Ice Hockey Club |url=http://www.psuwihc.com/2012/11/year-by-year-results.html | accessdate = August 8, 2014}}</ref>\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = team | conference = | postseason = | poll = both}}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead | name = Josh Brandwene | conference = [[College Hockey America]] | startyear = 2012 | endyear = 2020 }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Entry\n| championship =\n| season = 2012\u201313\n| name = Josh Brandwene\n| overall = 7\u201326\u20132\n| conference = 1\u201317\u20132\n| confstanding =